{"id":"1208.4122","submitter":"Stephen Bailey","authors":"Stephen Bailey","title":"Principal Component Analysis with Noisy and/or Missing Data","comments":"Accepted for publication in PASP; v2 with minor updates, mostly to\n  bibliography","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1086/668105","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.IM physics.data-an","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a method for performing Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on\nnoisy datasets with missing values. Estimates of the measurement error are used\nto weight the input data such that compared to classic PCA, the resulting\neigenvectors are more sensitive to the true underlying signal variations rather\nthan being pulled by heteroskedastic measurement noise. Missing data is simply\nthe limiting case of weight=0. The underlying algorithm is a noise weighted\nExpectation Maximization (EM) PCA, which has additional benefits of\nimplementation speed and flexibility for smoothing eigenvectors to reduce the\nnoise contribution. We present applications of this method on simulated data\nand QSO spectra from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Aug 2012 20:59:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Sep 2012 18:27:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-11"}
{"id":"1208.4123","submitter":"Roger Colbeck","authors":"Roger Colbeck and Renato Renner","title":"The completeness of quantum theory for predicting measurement outcomes","comments":"15 pages, 4 figures. This is an expanded and more pedagogical version\n  of arXiv:1005.5173 and arXiv:1111.6597 that discusses in detail the relation\n  to other results","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/978-94-017-7303-4","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The predictions that quantum theory makes about the outcomes of measurements\nare generally probabilistic. This has raised the question whether quantum\ntheory can be considered complete, or whether there could exist alternative\ntheories that provide improved predictions. Here we review recent work that\nconsiders arbitrary alternative theories, constrained only by the requirement\nthat they are compatible with a notion of \"free choice\" (defined with respect\nto a natural causal order). It is shown that quantum theory is \"maximally\ninformative\", i.e., there is no other compatible theory that gives improved\npredictions. Furthermore, any alternative maximally informative theory is\nnecessarily equivalent to quantum theory. This means that the state a system\nhas in such a theory is in one-to-one correspondence with its\nquantum-mechanical state (the wave function). In this sense, quantum theory is\ncomplete.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Aug 2012 21:09:29 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 11 Jul 2013 14:33:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-13"}
